When introducing yourself, people usually start off with their names. My name is Alyssa Tugaoen. The “Alyssa” is actually not pronounced like it normally is. It's pronounced as “A-ly-ssa”, rather than “A-lyss-a”. 

I was born and raised on Oahu, specifically in a small town named Wahiawa. I did not realize how small it was until I started college and would tell other people that live on Oahu that I’m from Wahiawa and they would respond with “where’s that?”

Throughout my childhood and most of my school years, I always thought that I would grow up to be a pharmacist. It wasn't until high school when I thought of going into business, specifically accounting. Whenever we would have guest speakers talk about their careers, my first choice would always be to hear the Accountants present. Now, I am currently aspiring a BBA in Accounting and MIS. 

I’m still debating whether or not I would also like to minor in Ilokano Language. Taking Ilokano 101 and 102 has tremendously improved my reading, writing, and oral communication skills. This language now flows naturally when I speak and it has opened my eyes to my culture.

I currently just finished an accounting internship and am now an accounting clerk at the Wahiawa Center for Community Health. This gave me many opportunities as I was able to get a hands-on, interactive experience.

This year, I hope to solidify my education goals and later move on to reinforce my future career goals.
